{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493027"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:53:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:53:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1204"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1204"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.06,0.56,0.19,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1204"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42481"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1204"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1204"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27459"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"665"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1940"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2019"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5346"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39439"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42481","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/42481"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old man is brought into the Emergency Department with a one hour history of acute onset, severe and constant central chest pain which radiates through to his back. He has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes. His medications include amlodipine, enalapril, metformin and semaglutide. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he is pale and sweating. His pulse rate is 96/min, blood pressure 170/110 mmHg, and SpO2 98% on room air. There is a soft systolic ejection murmur and the lung fields are clear. Examination of the abdomen is unremarkable, apart from a diminished left femoral pulse. An ECG does not show any acute ischaemic changes and a CT scan shows an aortic dissection starting 4 cm distal to the origin of the left subclavian artery and terminating at the level of the left common femoral artery.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first line plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous nitroprusside","Intravenous verapamil","Intravenous labetalol","Endovascular aneurysm repair","Thoracotomy and graft repair"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a type B aortic dissection sparing the ascending aorta and aortic root. The aim of initial treatment must be to reduce the blood pressure and pulse rate to reduce tension on the aortic wall -\u003Cstrong\u003E intravenous labetalol\u003C/strong\u003E is anti-hypertensive and a negative chronotrope, has rapid onset of action and is easily titratable making it the ideal agent in this setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFurther management of hypertension in a type B aortic dissection can involve an intravenous vasodilator (eg. \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous nitroprusside\u003C/strong\u003E), however this should only be given after the beta-blocker to prevent a reflex tachycardia (hence not most appropriate first line management) which risks rupturing the dissection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn intravenous calcium channel antagonist (eg. \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous verapamil\u003C/strong\u003E) may be applicable if the use of a beta-blocker is contra-indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn a type B aortic dissection, some form of radiological or surgical intervention (e.g. \u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003Eendovascular aneurysm repair \u003C/strong\u003Eor \u003Cstrong\u003Ethoracotomy graft repair\u003C/strong\u003E) may be considered once the patient has been stabilised. In addition, early surgical intervention would only be considered if there was evidence of vascular occlusion affecting a vital organ.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The management of Stanford B aortic dissection is conservative unless there are complications present (eg. vascular occlusion of a vital organ)."],"references":["Hiratzka LF, Bakris GL, Beckman JA, Bersin RM, Carr VF, Casey DE Jr, et al. 2010 ACCF/AHA/AATS/ACR/ASA/SCA/SCAI/SIR/STS/SVM guidelines for the diagnosis and management of patients with Thoracic Aortic Disease: a report of the American College of Cardiology Foundation/American Heart Association Task Force on Practice Guidelines, American Association for Thoracic Surgery, American College of Radiology, American Stroke Association, Society of Cardiovascular Anesthesiologists, Society for Cardiovascular Angiography and Interventions, Society of Interventional Radiology, Society of Thoracic Surgeons, and Society for Vascular Medicine. Circulation. 2010;121(13):e266-369. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20233780/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27459"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1204"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27459","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/27459"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-02-11T12:30:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-21T17:4